---
import BaseHead from '../components/BaseHead.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';
import IllustratedLobby from '../components/library/IllustratedLobby.astro';
import ReferenceDesk from '../components/ReferenceDesk.astro';
---
<!doctype html>
<html lang="en">
  <head>
    <BaseHead
      title="America's School Trust Library — An evidentiary archive of America's school trust lands and funds"
      description="Lands and funds set aside since 1785 to support America's public K-12 schools."
    />
  </head>
  <body class="min-h-screen bg-archive-paper text-ink mode-standard">
    <Header />
    <main class="mx-auto max-w-5xl p-4 sm:p-8">
      <IllustratedLobby />
      <section
        class="border-b border-slate-200 pb-10"
        style="background-image: linear-gradient(to bottom, rgba(250, 249, 246, 0.92), rgba(250, 249, 246, 0.96)), url('/img/maps/royce-1899-us.jpg'); background-size: cover; background-position: center; background-repeat: no-repeat; padding: 2.5rem 1.5rem; border-radius: 4px; margin: 0 -1rem;"
      >
        <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold tracking-tight sm:text-5xl">
          America's School Trust Library
        </h1>
        <p class="mt-3 text-lg text-slate-600 sm:text-xl">
          An evidentiary archive of America's school trust lands and funds
        </p>
        <p class="mt-6 text-base font-medium text-slate-800 sm:text-lg">
          Lands and funds set aside since 1785 to support America's public K-12 schools.
        </p>
        <div class="prose prose-slate mt-6 max-w-none">
          <p>
            In 1785, before the Constitution, the United States began setting aside public
            land for public schools. Some states turned that inheritance into permanent funds
            worth billions. Others sold it, raided it, or quietly let it disappear.
          </p>
          <p>
            This library is for inspecting what happened. Read the history, find your state,
            map the architecture, audit the ledger. Every figure carries a confidence badge.
            Every blank cell is a deliberate signal.
          </p>
          <p>
            Start with your state, the national map, or a short guide to how the school-trust
            compact worked — and how it drifted.
          </p>
        </div>
      </section>

      <section class="home-poster home-poster--top mt-6" aria-label="The Library's argument in one image">
        <a href="/why/" class="block">
          <img
            src="/img/hero/hero_v1_2026-05-06.png"
            alt="Three-panel diagram: 1785 the experiment begins; 240 years of drift; 2026 the architects of the next century's trusts."
            class="w-full rounded-md shadow-md"
          />
        </a>
        <p class="mt-3 text-center text-sm italic text-slate-600">
          America wrote a perpetual trust into the geometry of the country in 1785. Two centuries of data on what happens. The architecture for the next century's intergenerational trusts depends on it.
          <a href="/why/" class="ml-1 text-blue-700 underline">Why this matters →</a>
        </p>
      </section>

      <aside class="launch-announcement">
        <span class="eyebrow">New</span>
        <p>
          <strong>This library opened May 2026 and is expanding rapidly.</strong> New
          library entries, white papers, and primary sources are being added monthly.
          <a href="/updates/">See what's new this month →</a>
        </p>
      </aside>

      <section class="mt-10" aria-label="Three doors">
        <ul class="grid grid-cols-1 gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm transition hover:shadow">
            <a href="/start/" class="block">
              <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
                Start Here
              </p>
              <h2 class="mt-2 text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-blue-700 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                What are school trust lands?
              </h2>
              <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-700">
                The 1785 land ordinance, the trust that followed, the drift, and how to read
                what's on this site. Ten minutes.
              </p>
            </a>
          </li>
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm transition hover:shadow">
            <a href="/reading/" class="block">
              <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
                Find Your State
              </p>
              <h2 class="mt-2 text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-blue-700 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                Reading Room
              </h2>
              <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-700">
                Every state has an entry. Read your state's full <strong>state dossier</strong>, or jump
                to its row in the Counting House and its polygon on the Atlas.
              </p>
            </a>
          </li>
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm transition hover:shadow">
            <a href="/atlas/" class="block">
              <p class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
                See the National Pattern
              </p>
              <h2 class="mt-2 text-xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-blue-700 underline-offset-2 hover:underline">
                Atlas
              </h2>
              <p class="mt-3 text-sm text-slate-700">
                One map, four lenses. Era cohort, fund corpus, federal grant acreage,
                transparency status. The same fifty states answer four different questions.
              </p>
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-12" aria-label="Featured entry points">
        <h2 class="text-xs font-semibold uppercase tracking-wide text-slate-500">
          Featured entries
        </h2>
        <ul class="mt-4 grid grid-cols-1 gap-4 sm:grid-cols-3">
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight">
              <a href="/reading/us-or/" class="text-blue-700 underline hover:text-blue-900">
                Oregon — the live test case
              </a>
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
              Strong constitutional architecture (1857), the Elliott State Forest decoupling
              (2017–2022), and the January 2026 Court of Appeals standing victory in
              <em>Advocates for School Trust Lands v. State of Oregon</em>. The case OASTL is
              currently litigating.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight">
              <a href="/reading/us-ut/" class="text-blue-700 underline hover:text-blue-900">
                Utah — the recovery case
              </a>
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
              Constituency rebuilt what architecture alone could not protect. The clearest
              national model for how a breached trust gets back on track.
            </p>
          </li>
          <li class="rounded-lg border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 shadow-sm">
            <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold tracking-tight">
              <a href="/reading/us-ms/" class="text-blue-700 underline hover:text-blue-900">
                Mississippi — the lost inheritance
              </a>
            </h3>
            <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-slate-700">
              Section 16 history shows what depletion looks like when no recovery occurred.
              Sixteenth sections sold for as little as $1 per acre in the 1820s.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="mt-10 rounded-md border border-slate-200 bg-white p-5 text-sm text-slate-700 shadow-sm">
        <p>
          Three rooms are live today: Reading Room, Atlas, Counting House. Newsroom and
          Updates also live as of May 2026, in early form. Three more rooms open later in
          2026: Records Room (curated primary sources, opening month 3), Court Room (case
          law and litigation, opening month 5-6), Breach &amp; Recovery (drift case
          studies, opening month 6-9).
        </p>
      </section>

      <section
        class="mt-10 rounded-lg border-l-4 border-amber-500 bg-amber-50 p-5 shadow-sm"
        aria-label="Why some numbers are blank"
      >
        <h2 class="text-base font-semibold tracking-tight text-amber-900">
          Why some numbers are blank
        </h2>
        <p class="mt-2 text-sm text-amber-900">
          You'll see "Awaiting State Disclosure" badges across this library. Twelve states
          publish complete school-trust accounting today. Thirty-eight don't. The Counting House
          makes that visible because that absence is the finding — not a defect of this site.
          Visible incompleteness with correction pathways is the fastest path to credibility, and
          it's the only way a public ledger of public trusts can earn its name.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section class="home-poster home-poster--footer mx-auto mt-12 max-w-2xl" aria-label="The Library's argument in one image — parting summary">
        <a href="/reading/sacred-compact-prologue/" class="block">
          <img
            src="/img/hero/hero_v1_2026-05-06.png"
            alt="Three-panel diagram: 1785 the experiment begins; 240 years of drift; 2026 the architects of the next century's trusts."
            class="w-full rounded-md shadow-sm"
          />
        </a>
        <p class="mt-2 text-center text-xs italic text-slate-500">
          The Library's argument, in one image. Click through to read the Sacred Compact.
        </p>
      </section>

      <ReferenceDesk />
    </main>
    <Footer />
  </body>
</html>
